url = {https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0885392422011484},
author = {Rebecca L. Yamarik and Mara Flannery and Kaitlyn {Van Allen} and Allison Cuthel and Jennifer Curtis and Laraine Chiu and Inez Brandon and Keith Goldfeld and Corita Grudzen},
abstract = {Outcomes
1. Upon completion, participants will self-report the ability to describe the impact of a telephonic palliative care program on a patient's quality of life 2. Upon completion, participants will self-report the different layers of support that a palliative care telephonic nurse program can apply to vulnerable populations (eg, seriously ill and older adults)
Research objective
The emergency department (ED) serves as the healthcare safety net for the most vulnerable older adults. Palliative care interventions in the ED can capture high-risk patients at a time of crisis and improve patient-centered outcomes. Nurse-led telephonic care is cost effective and more accessible to seriously ill patients than face-to-face outpatient palliative care encounters.
Study design
The Emergency Medicine Palliative Care Access (EMPallA) study is an ongoing PCORI-funded, multicenter, two-armed randomized trial comparing two models of palliative care for patients recruited from the ED: nurse-led telephonic case management and specialty outpatient palliative care. The study enrolled patients aged 50+ with serious life-limiting organ failure or advanced cancer from 19 participating EDs across the United States. Patients in the telephonic arm received weekly or biweekly calls by a palliative nurse over a 6-month period. Nurses completed an end of intervention implementation checklist at the 6-month time point reporting on advance care planning (ACP), caregiver-specific goals, and status (eg, vital, physical, functional health) of the patient at study completion.
Results
A total of 505 patients had completed checklists. 283 (56%) were female, 49 (10%) were Latinx, and 166 (33%) were Black. The median age was 66 years old. 245 patients (49%) completed all 6 months of the intervention, 173 (34%) withdrew or were lost to follow-up, and 31 (6%) enrolled in hospice within 6 months of enrollment. 210 (43%) completed ACP and named a healthcare proxy.
Conclusions
Nurse-led telephonic care for vulnerable, seriously ill patients recruited from the ED was successful in engaging patients and completing ACP. Telephonic palliative nursing may influence a patient's quality of life through an additional layer of supportive, accessible care among multiple vulnerable populations, indicating a continued need for such initiatives.}
}
