abstract = {Outcomes
1. Define narrative competence and analyze its role in direct patient care and as part of a hospice and palliative care practice. 2. Evaluate the impact of incorporating narrative training into a palliative medicine fellowship curriculum.
Background
Narrative medical practice is the ability to recognize, absorb, metabolize, interpret, and be moved by patients’ stories of illness. Narrative competence includes skills of attention, representation, and affiliation. Being attuned to patients’ experiences, effectively interpreting stories of illness, and reflective practice enhance clinical effectiveness.
Methods
A narrative medicine (NM) series was incorporated into HPM fellowship. Fellows participated in 3 to 4 sessions which included (1) didactic principles/practices, (2) close examination of text, (3) reflective writing, and (4) dialogue with peers and faculty. HPM physician faculty completed coursework at the program in narrative medicine at Columbia University and series curriculum was informed by that program's teaching. Fellows completed pre and post 4-point Likert-style surveys.
Results
Pre- and postintervention surveys (n=36) were administered to 20 HPM fellows. Four surveys were missing due to absences. Pre- and postintervention, fellows reported high responses to (1) importance of eliciting patient's story (μ=3.94, 4), (2) enjoying patients’ stories (μ=3.72, 3.83), and (3) openness to learning narrative skills (μ=3.83, 3.94). Postintervention, fellows reported significant increases in NM knowledge (μ=2.17, 3.72, p = <0.01) and confidence in ability to successfully elicit and appreciate a patient's story (μ=2.22, 3.39, p = <0.01).
Discussion
The pre and post high levels of value, enjoyment, and interest in narrative skills may represent selection bias in this cohort of HPM fellows. Post surveys indicated a significant increase in perceived understanding of NM and possession of narrative skills, which may be due to the intervention or other components of HPM training. Results support the potential benefits of a NM curriculum within an HPM fellowship related to skills required to conduct a comprehensive palliative assessment.
Conclusion
Integration of an educational NM series was associated with a significant increase in narrative knowledge and competence and may be a meaningful curricular component of HPM fellowship training.}
}
